  "local_port": 42894,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the stats for WordPress, Drupal, and Joomla installs on the web?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, WordPress, Drupal, and Joomla remain among the most popular content management systems (CMS) used for building websites. Below are the latest available statistics and insights into their market presence and usage:\n\n### **1. WordPress**\n\n- **Market Share:** WordPress is the leading CMS globally, powering approximately **43-45%** of all websites on the internet. This dominance spans various types of websites, from blogs and small business sites to large enterprise portals.\n  \n- **Active Installations:** WordPress boasts over **600 million** active websites, including WordPress.com-hosted sites and self-hosted (WordPress.org) installations.\n\n- **Usage Trends:**\n  - **Themes and Plugins:** There is a vast ecosystem of over **100,000** themes and **58,000** plugins available, allowing for extensive customization and functionality extensions.\n  - **Community and Support:** A large, active community contributes to continuous improvements, security updates, and a wealth of resources for users.\n\n- **Strengths:**\n  - **Ease of Use:** User-friendly interface suitable for beginners.\n  - **Flexibility:** Suitable for a wide range of website types.\n  - **SEO-Friendly:** Built-in SEO capabilities and numerous SEO plugins.\n\n### **2. Drupal**\n\n- **Market Share:** Drupal holds about **2-3%** of the CMS market share. While not as widespread as WordPress, it is highly regarded for more complex and large-scale websites, especially in enterprise and governmental sectors.\n\n- **Active Installations:** Estimates suggest there are over **1.5 million** active Drupal websites.\n\n- **Usage Trends:**\n  - **Modules:** Drupal has around **47,000** modules available, providing extensive functionality and customization.\n  - **Security:** Known for robust security features, making it a preferred choice for high-security applications.\n\n- **Strengths:**\n  - **Flexibility and Scalability:** Ideal for complex, large-scale websites requiring customizable content structures.\n  - **Advanced User Permissions:** Fine-grained access control suitable for multi-user environments.\n  - **Developer-Friendly:** Offers powerful APIs and a strong framework for developers.\n\n### **3. Joomla**\n\n- **Market Share:** Joomla accounts for approximately **1.5-2%** of the CMS market share. It serves as a middle ground between WordPress and Drupal, offering more flexibility than WordPress and greater ease of use than Drupal.\n\n- **Active Installations:** There are roughly **4 million** Joomla websites active online.\n\n- **Usage Trends:**\n  - **Extensions:** Joomla has over **8,000** extensions and templates available to enhance functionality and design.\n  - **Community Support:** A dedicated community provides support, updates, and a range of resources for users and developers.\n\n- **Strengths:**\n  - **Flexibility:** Suitable for a variety of websites, including e-commerce, social networking, and corporate portals.\n  - **Multilingual Support:** Built-in multilingual capabilities without requiring additional plugins.\n  - **User Management:** Robust user management features, making it suitable for community-driven sites.\n\n### **Comparative Insights**\n\n- **Ease of Use:** WordPress is generally considered the most user-friendly, especially for beginners. Joomla offers more complexity, while Drupal is often chosen for highly customized and complex sites requiring developer expertise.\n\n- **Customization and Extensibility:** All three CMS platforms offer a wide range of themes/templates and plugins/extensions. However, WordPress has the most extensive ecosystem, followed by Drupal and Joomla.\n\n- **Security:** Drupal is often favored for its strong security features, making it a preferred choice for governmental and enterprise-level websites. WordPress can be secure with proper management and updates, while Joomla also provides solid security features.\n\n- **Performance and Scalability:** Drupal excels in handling large, complex websites with high traffic. WordPress, while scalable, may require optimization and robust hosting solutions for very large sites. Joomla offers a balance between scalability and performance.\n\n### **Trends and Future Outlook**\n\n- **WordPress** continues to grow, especially with the increasing adoption of headless CMS architectures and the integration of REST APIs, making it versatile for various applications beyond traditional websites.\n\n- **Drupal** maintains a steady presence in niches requiring high security and customization. The release of Drupal 10 introduced modern features and improved developer experience, likely sustaining its relevance in the enterprise sector.\n\n- **Joomla** remains a solid choice for medium-sized projects but faces stiff competition from both WordPress and Drupal. Efforts to modernize and streamline its user experience may influence its future adoption rates.\n\n### **Sources and References**\n\n- **W3Techs:** Provides detailed statistics on CMS usage across the web. [W3Techs CMS Usage Statistics](https://w3techs.com/technologies/overview/content_management)\n\n- **BuiltWith:** Offers insights into technology trends, including CMS market shares. [BuiltWith CMS Market Share](https://trends.builtwith.com/cms)\n\n- **Official CMS Websites:** For the most accurate and up-to-date information, refer to the official websites and community updates for [WordPress](https://wordpress.org/about/stats/), [Drupal](https://www.drupal.org/about/stats), and [Joomla](https://www.joomla.org/about-joomla.html).\n\n*Please note that CMS market shares and installation numbers are continually evolving. For the most current statistics, it's advisable to consult real-time analytics platforms like W3Techs or BuiltWith.*",
